The really best solution to avoid all this mess (autoexec.bat...) is to use Ant.  If you are not working with Ant, invest a few hours to set it running.

Ok, to run Ant, you have to set the ANT_HOME environment variable...

You can then easily and precisely define what your classpath is and forget about these $%&#^ global variables :-)

What I do:

- in my build.xml file, I do not make any assumptions about where my project will be compiled.  No explicit reference to the classpath is made
- the classpath is defined with the &lt;classpath&gt;&lt;/classpath&gt; task
- the script needs some variable (like the location of the javahelp libs) so I have a mk.bat script that call ant and passes all the needed variables with the -D option
- instead of &#39;ant build&#39; I type &#39;mk build&#39;

to build the project on another environment, only the mk.bat file must be changed

-Vladimir

build.xml

  &lt;property name=&quot;build_dir&quot;    value=&quot;build&quot; /&gt;
  &lt;property name=&quot;src_dir&quot;      value=&quot;src&quot; /&gt;

   &lt;target name=&quot;build&quot; depends=&quot;init&quot;&gt;
     &lt;javac srcdir=&quot;${src_dir}&quot;
            destdir=&quot;${build_dir}&quot;
            debug=&quot;on&quot;
            verbose=&quot;off&quot;
            deprecation=&quot;on&quot;&gt;
       &lt;classpath&gt;
          &lt;pathelement location=&quot;${javahelp_home}/lib/jh.jar&quot; /&gt;
       &lt;/classpath&gt;
     &lt;/javac&gt;
     &lt;copy todir=&quot;${build_dir}&quot; &gt;
       &lt;fileset dir=&quot;${src_dir}&quot;
                excludes=&quot;**/*.java,**/*.*~&quot; /&gt;
     &lt;/copy&gt;
  &lt;/target&gt;

mk.bat:

c:&#92;...&#92;ant.exe -Djavahelp_home=${JHHOME}/javahelp $1
